subSubSection.paragraph:
Habitat. Mocquard (1896:59) noted the species “habite les rochers” [inhabits rocks] in Guinea . Pasqual (1962) remarked that this species favors thatched roofs in Nigeria . Knoepffler (1966) described a specimen (MBG 0519) that was collected from a cave in Gabon where an enormous colony of bats and rockfowl (
Picathartes oreas
) were nesting, but the snake’s stomach was empty. Leston & Hughes (1968) found several snakes in trees of a cocoa farm in Ghana . Roux-Estève (1969) documented a subadult that was taken from a palm tree near a grove in Ivory Coast . Hughes (2000) explained how many authors restricted the species to forest (e.g., Perret 1961 ; Isemonger 1962 ; Roux- Estève 1969; Hughes 1983 ), but in fact, it occurs in several different habitats including savanna and urban areas, always seeming to seek out places with trees.
